Anonymous Mon 14 May 2018 23:05:03 No.15772939 Report
Quoted By: >>15773099 >>15773777 >>15773810
>>15772045
This. Effective feedback isn't painless; it requires relatively close reading, a fair amount of thought, and preferably some familiarity with how stories and prose are put together. It's easy to say whether or not you liked something. Explaining why is substantially more difficult. Explaining why while also remaining unbiased by your own writing style complicates the matter further, as it's often difficult to gauge the borders of style and quality. We all have different ways of tackling the same problems, and we can only really instruct others in our own ways. The balancing act between trying to explain to someone how to write better and how to write more like you is a delicate one.

This is complete conjecture, but I'd wager most readers are here for their own entertainment and relaxation, and don't care to put that much effort into their light reading. That's completely fair. That said, I wish posters wouldn't shy away even from less specific answers. Even if you can't articulate exactly why you do or don't like something, if you try, there's a decent chance you'll spark a discussion on the craft in at least general terms. Given we have different ways of solving the same problems, one of the most useful things we can do is compare and discuss them. of course, while that's great for writefags, it's not worth much to people who are only here to read. I've never been clear on how welcome that sort of discussion is.

>>15772456
